                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS_Bodl_854-item1">
                     <locus from="21" to="235" type="inferredEnd">(p. 21)</locus>
                     <author key="person_197450766">John of Glastonbury</author>
                     <title key="work_2835">Historia de rebus Glastoniensibus</title>
                     <rubric>De antiquitate vetuste ecclesie beate Marie Glastonie et de quadam augmentacione quam Sanctus Dauid diuina reuelacione adiecit et in honore beate Marie consecrauit</rubric>
                     <incipit>Anno post passionem Domini tricesimo primo</incipit>
                     <note>Prologue on p. 4</note>
                     <note>Several leaves are wanting at the end, the text ending with 'missum est decretum eleccionis diocesano episcopo vt' (p. 238 of James P. Carley's edition [Boydell, 1985])</note>
                     <note>Some words and sentences, especially on pp. 375-431, are ineffectively deleted by someone who objected to the name and deeds of popes</note>
                     <note>The text is a direct copy of <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_379">MS. Ashmole 790</ref>; so much so that the name of the scribe of MS. Ashmole 790, 
                        Thomas Wason, is copied on p. 110
                        </note>
                     <note>The treatise was edited by Thomas Hearne from other manuscripts in 1726, but Hearne printed notes on this manuscript by Gerard Langbaine (1609-1658) at vol. i, p. lix of his edition</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
